P.5 Falsifiability





Scarlet is ruled out if:

S_8(z) < S_8^{\Lambda\mathrm{CDM}} \quad \text{for } z > 2



Scarlet survives if:



suppression appears only at late times,
the CMB remains unchanged,
growth shows a yield transition.









P.6 Yield Epoch and Growth Bifurcation





We define the Yield Epoch as:

t_y \equiv 11.1\,\mathrm{Gyr} \quad \Longleftrightarrow \quad z_y \approx 0.3



For t < t_y:

\eta(t) = 0



For t \ge t_y:

\eta(t) \neq 0



This epoch coincides with the observed late-time bifurcation between early-universe and late-universe growth amplitudes.



Thus, the Scarlet Yield Epoch provides a physical interpretation of the growth bifurcation:

it represents the onset of macroscopic transport fatigue rather than a modification of gravity or initial conditions.








P.7 Energy Accounting and Torsional Fatigue





The Rayleigh dissipation functional:

\Phi(\dot{\zeta}) = \tfrac{1}{2} \eta \dot{\zeta}^2

represents work done against torsional resistance.



This energy is not destroyed but converted into internal degrees of freedom of the spacetime substrate:



E_{\text{transport}} \rightarrow E_{\text{fatigue}}



interpreted as:



accumulated torsional strain,
microscopic substrate excitation,
effective â€œbedrock heating.â€




Therefore:



Local conservation laws hold.
Microscopic gauge dynamics remain unitary.
No violation of the First Law of Thermodynamics occurs.




The observed 0.21 slip fraction corresponds to finite transport efficiency, not missing energy.








P.8 Summary





Scarlet introduces:



an Updated Lagrangian formulation,
a Rayleigh dissipation functional,
a late-time transport-loss mechanism,




without violating:



general relativity,
gauge symmetry,
microscopic unitarity.




It is compatible with:



N-body solvers,
hydrodynamic codes,
Boltzmann hierarchies,
discrete spacetime models,




using a single time-dependent parameter \eta(t) such that:

\eta(t < t_y) = 0, \quad \eta(t \ge t_y) \neq 0








